<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-640-978 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 640 978.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 15 1991 n637 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Philips to show HDTV. (high-definition television)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doherty, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Philips' North American unit plans to demonstrate its MotionPicture Expert Group (MPEG)-based high-definition television(HDTV) digital video compression technology at a 1991 televisionindustry trade show in Las Vegas.andP;  The demonstration by Philips ispart of a plan to convince members of the television industry toswitch to digital video studio technology before formal HDTVequipment production begins.andP;  Many television studios seem readyto make the switch, and engineers from Columbia University saythat it is now a cost-effective solution because of reducedoperating costs.andP;  Philips' compression technology couldconceivably place as many as 10 or 12 picture signals over asingle cable channel.andP;  Such a picture would have no extraneousnoise.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Philips Gloeilampenfabrieken N.V. (Product development).andO;Topic:     ExhibitsHigh-Definition TelevisionDigital VideoData CompressionProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Philips' video-compression encoder squeezes broadcast video.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>